Wahba / TRIAD / QUEST external reference — attitude determination
=================================================================

p4_wahba_reference.txt holds reference optimal attitudes for a set of noiseless,
deterministic Wahba (weighted vector-observation attitude) problems, computed by
an independent third-party authority and used to externally validate Kshana's own
attitude solvers (see tests/wahba_reference.rs). These files are not part of the
Kshana source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages.

Oracle
------
scipy 1.13.1 — the canonical scientific-computing library (Virtanen et al.,
"SciPy 1.0: fundamental algorithms for scientific computing in Python", Nature
Methods 17, 2020; open source, BSD), specifically
`scipy.spatial.transform.Rotation.align_vectors`. That routine solves Wahba's
problem by the **Kabsch / Markley SVD** method: it forms the attitude profile
matrix from the weighted vector pairs and takes its singular-value decomposition
to read off the unique optimal proper rotation.

Independence
------------
This is a genuinely different algorithm and codebase from Kshana's solvers, which
compute the SAME uniquely-defined Wahba minimiser by:
  * Davenport's q-method — largest-eigenvalue eigenvector of the 4x4 K-matrix via
    a self-contained symmetric Jacobi eigensolver (`solve_davenport`);
  * QUEST (Shuster & Oh 1981) — derivative-free root of Davenport's
    characteristic polynomial + Gibbs-vector quaternion recovery (`solve_quest`);
  * TRIAD (Black 1964) — closed-form two-vector attitude (`triad`).
None of these re-uses scipy's SVD path, so scipy is an independent oracle for the
noiseless deterministic optimum. (SVD vs eigen/K-matrix vs closed-form all agree
on the unique noiseless Wahba solution.)

Convention pin
--------------
Kshana's attitude matrix A maps reference->body (A r = b). scipy's
align_vectors(a, b, weights) returns R minimising sum_i w_i || a_i - R b_i ||^2,
i.e. R b ~ a; feeding a=body, b=reference yields exactly Kshana's A (verified to
~3e-16 against a known ground-truth rotation before pinning). The Rust test does
NOT compare raw quaternion components (which carry a sign ambiguity and a
body<->nav convention); it compares DCMs via the frame-agnostic attitude-error
angle — the rotation angle of A_kshana @ A_scipy^T — which is zero iff the two
attitudes are physically identical.

Scope (honest)
--------------
Validates the NOISELESS, deterministic Wahba-optimal attitude (TRIAD / Davenport
q-method / QUEST) against an independent SVD oracle. The noisy Monte-Carlo
"q-method beats TRIAD in RMS attitude error" STATISTICAL efficiency claim is NOT
covered here and stays honestly MODELLED. See src/verification.rs.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_p4_wahba_reference.py (scipy 1.13.1 +
numpy 1.26.4). All real-valued inputs/outputs use Python repr so the Rust test
parses identical f64. Regenerable fully offline with no Kshana code involved.

Format
------
'#'-prefixed comments, then per case:
  CASE  <name> <kind> <n>          kind='quest' if QUEST-safe (rotation << 180 deg)
  OBS   <rx> <ry> <rz> <w>         n lines: reference direction + weight
  BODY  <bx> <by> <bz>             n lines: body direction (= A r, noiseless)
  DCM   <row0> ; DCM <row1> ; DCM <row2>   scipy optimal reference->body A, row-major
  RSSD  <residual>                 scipy residual root-sum-of-squares (~0, noiseless)
  ANGLE <angle_rad>                ground-truth rotation angle (informational)
  ENDCASE
